 Our Great Leaders, Moses and David: The Doctrine of Grace in Sifre Deuteronomy -- tPart 2 Ancient Israelite Religion and Its Near Eastern Context -- tOne God for Many: Philological Glosses on Monotheism -- tThe Divinity of Humankind in the Bible and the Ancient Near East: A New Mesopotamian Parallel -- tDoes God Deceive? An Examination of the Dark Side of Isaiah's Prophecy -- tThe Unique Features of Ezekiel's Sanctuary -- tOn the Place of Psalm 21 in Israelite Royal Ideology -- tMyth and Syntax in Psalm 93 -- tThe Problem of Evil in the Book of Job -- tPart 3 Ancient Israelite Literary Tradition -- tExamples of Restatement in the Laws of Hammurabi -- tLiterary-Critical Issues in the Hebrew Bible from an Assyriological Perspective: Additions and Omissions -- tBiblical Naming Reports with -- tThe Ancient Critical Misunderstanding of Exodus 21:22-25 and Its Implications for the Current Debate on Abortion -- tLinen and the Linguistic Dating of P -- tA New Approach to Metaphor in Biblical Poetry -- tThe Four Private Persons Who Lost Their Share in the World to Come: The Judgment of m. Sanh. 10:2 -- tHermeneutical Freedom and Constraint in Jewish Bible Exegesis -- tIndex of Authors -- tIndex of Scripture0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aJeffrey H. Tigay, A. M. Ellis Professor of Hebrew and Semitic Languages and Literatures at the University of Pennsylvania, master teacher and scholar extraordinaire, conservative rabbi and lifelong student of Torah receives due ovation in this exceptional volume, a tribute to his indelible impression on Jewish scholarship and pedagogy.The volume is arranged according to Professor Tigay's primary topics of interest: deuteronomic studies, ancient Israelite religion and its Near Eastern context, and ancient Israelite literary tradition. The reader will enjoy diverse studies such as "Gender Transformation and Transgression: Contextualizing the Prohibition of Cross-dressing in Deuteronomy 22:5," "The Problem of Evil in the Book of Job," and "Linen and the Linguistic Dating of P" and will value the erudition of scholars such as Moshe Greenberg, Emanuel Tov, Gary Rendsburg, William Hallo, and Baruch Levine.In the customary appreciations and throughout the volume, colleagues, students, and friends laud Professor Tigay's intellectual tenacity, relational warmth, pedagogical prowess, and devotion to Torah. A former student aptly speaks for those who know him best: "A scholar's immortality lies in his or her work. It rests too in his or her students and in the respect won from his or her colleagues. A Festschrift like this one for Jeff Tigay is merely a token of that legacy, the acknowledgment by his students and colleagues that the work is indeed worth celebrating." This legacy will surely be a boon and delight to the reader.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh1 aAster, Shawn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerlin, Adele, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarasik, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCogan, Mordechai, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCohen, Chaim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEichler, Barry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFox, Nili Sacher, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFox, Nili, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGeller, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGilad, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGlatt-Gilad, David A., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/voc